Testing has also been ramped up with the number of tests conducted up by 43 percent in the past week. JOHANNESBURG - South Africa's death toll due to COVID-19 has increased by 43 percent in the past week. On Saturday, the health department reported seven more deaths, bringing the total to 123. This means the death toll since last Saturday has increased by 37 from 86. READ: COVID-19 death toll in SA rises to 123 At the same time, the number of positive tests has increased by 45 percent to 6,336. Testing has also been ramped up with the number of tests conducted up by 43 percent in the past week. More than 13,000 people were tested in the last 24 hours, the highest number of tests in a 24-hour cycle since testing started. IN NUMBERS: COVID-19 in SA The good news is that recoveries have jumped by 73 percent in the past week with more than 2,500 people who tested positive having already recovered. The health department has also begun to study the patterns of deaths to identify areas of high risk. The findings show that 58 percent of those that died were men and 42 percent were women. READ: WHO says virus 'natural in origin' Only one person younger than 30 has died. The median age of those who died was 64. Like in other countries, hypertension, diabetes and cardiac disease are the three most common co-morbidities associated with serious illness from COVID-19. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.